Hotel Bookings Analysis¶

Introduction¶

The hotel bookings dataset includes booking information for Resort Hotel and City Hotel. It contains information about demographics, reservations, requests, payment methods and amounts, and duration of stay for each hotel.

The adr variable in the data is the average daily rate which has been computed by dividing total staying transactions by total nights stayed. The market_segment variable describes where the incoming bookings are made from (TA/TO meaning Travel Agency and Tour Operator, Corporate, Direct, etc.)

We are exploring peak times of hotel stays through examining the arrival date variable and using this information to predict future bookings. Additionally, we will be analyzing what influeces the adr in order to determine how to get the best deal at each hotel. We will be also analyze what variables can help hotels predict if someone will cancel their booking reservation. Lastly, we will explore which market segments should hotels spend the most resources on.

Packages¶

The dplyr package is being used for data manipulation. Some functions used from the package in this report are mutate(), select(), filter(), and summarize().

The ggplot2 package is being used in this report to create graphics and visualizations of the data.

The lubridate package is being used to convert dates in more easily accessible data types and formats. Some functions used from the package in this report are make_date() and mdy().

Tidying Data¶

We tidy the data in order make it easy to use for data analysis, the NA values in certain columns have been removed and the data types for columns containing dates have been changed from character type to date type.

Additionally for the market segments variable we have removed "Undefined" as there was only one booking with an undefined market segment and this does not provide any information to the hotels.

Question Number 1:¶

When are peak times for hotel bookings and how are other variables affected during these times? Determining peak times can help hotels determine prices according to the demand during certain times.

To answer this question, a new table will be formulated and will include the average daily rate as well as how much in advance people book their room. These will be grouped by the arrival month.

In [101]:
peak_month_times <- 
tidy %>%

group_by (arrival_date_month = as.numeric (arrival_date_month)) %>%
summarize ( count = n(), mean_lead_time = mean(lead_time), mean_avg_daily_rate = mean(adr)) %>%


arrange(desc(count))

Conclusion : By looking at the newly formulated tables, we see that the most booking are made for August, July, and May. These are Summer/Spring months, so it makes sense that most people travel during this time. We can also see that the average lead time and average daily rates for these month tend to be higher than non-peak months. This suggests that people book more in advance during peak times and prices are higher - probably because there is so much demand during this time.

Question Number 2 :¶

We would like to examine the influence that different variables have on the average daily rate, in order to determine how to get the best deal at each hotel. In the last question, we determined that during peak times the average daily rate is higher, and now we would like to determine what effect the room type and lead time have on the price.

In [105]:
tidy_resort <- tidy %>% filter(hotel=="Resort Hotel")
tidy_city <- tidy %>% filter(hotel=="City Hotel")
In [106]:
tidy_resort %>% group_by(reserved_room_type) %>% mutate(median=median(adr)) %>% ggplot() + geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(x=reorder(reserved_room_type,median),y=adr)) + xlab("Reserved Room Type") + ylab("ADR") + ggtitle("Resort Hotel - Reserved Room Type vs. ADR")
tidy_city %>% filter(adr<4000) %>% group_by(reserved_room_type) %>% mutate(median=median(adr)) %>% ggplot() + geom_boxplot(mapping=aes(x=reorder(reserved_room_type,median),y=adr)) + xlab("Reserved Room Type") + ylab("ADR") +ggtitle("City Hotel - Reserved Room Type vs. ADR")

Since the rooms are divided into different categories based on type, it is safe to assume that they may differ in price. By creating a boxplot for each individual hotel, we are able to see not only which rooms are more expensive, but also that the ranking of prices for each room type differs between the two hotels. By restricting adr values for the city hotel to less than 4000, we are able to get rid of the one extreme value that is most likely an error, and make the scale of each plot equal so the price comparisons are very easy to visualize. By organizing the plots by median average daily rates, it is easy to see which rooms are the best deal for each hotel. Although the city hotel has more expensive rooms on average, it has a better deal for some of the room types. For example, if a family was interested in renting a C type room, they would likely find a better deal for it at the city hotel.

In [107]:
tidy_resort %>% ggplot() +geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=lead_time,y=adr)) + xlab("Lead Time") + ylab("ADR") + ggtitle("Resort Hotel - Lead Time vs. ADR")

tidy_city  %>% ggplot() +geom_smooth(mapping=aes(x=lead_time,y=adr)) + xlab("Lead Time") + ylab("ADR") +ggtitle("City Hotel - Lead Time vs. ADR")

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

`geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam' and formula 'y ~ s(x, bs = "cs")'

By plotting lead time with adr for each hotel, we are able to see how effective booking ahead of time is for getting a lower rate. We can see that prices at the City Hotel are more consistent, but that typically, the farther one books in advance, the lower rate they will get. Prices for Resort hotel fluctuate over a wider range, and one is not necessarily guaranteed a lower rate for booking earlier. In fact, after 600 days, there is a sharp increase in prices, and before 50 days, the price is much lower. This may be because the hotel is trying to fill its empty rooms at the last minute. Therefore, if a customer is planning ahead for a trip, they will likely recieve a better deal staying at the City Hotel, but if it is a last minute trip, the Resort Hotel would be a safer bet.

By plotting the ADR against both the room type and lead time, we see that they are closely related, so customers are able to get a much lower rate if they account for these different factors, and choose the hotel that best suits their needs for the cheapest price.

Question Number 3 :¶

What variables can help hotels predict if someone will cancel their booking reservation?

Cancellations can cause some problems for hotels when scheduling staff etc. It may be useful to have some red flags for hotels to watch out for so cancellations don't sneak up on them and they may be able to base overbooking on these red flags.

To answer this question, is_cancel will be compared to the variables prev_cancellations, lead_time and market_segment. This will be done by finding the proportion of cancellations per value of the independent variable for prev_cancellations and lead_time. For market_segment, the proportion of cancellations per each type of market segment must be found. These results will then be displayed visually using techniques we have learned in class.

Investigate if number of previous cancellations increases the likelihood that someone will cancel their reservation by finding the proportion of cancellations based on the value of previous cancellations. Then use geom_point and geom_smooth in a faceted ggplot by the hotel variable to visualize the results.

In [108]:
prev_cancel_table <- tidy %>%
select(hotel, is_canceled, previous_cancellations) %>%
group_by(hotel, previous_cancellations, is_canceled) %>%
summarize(num_cancel = n()) %>%
spread(key = is_canceled, value = num_cancel) %>%
mutate(not_canceled = `0`, canceled = `1`) %>%
select(hotel, previous_cancellations, not_canceled, canceled) %>%
mutate(not_canceled = ifelse(is.na(not_canceled) == TRUE, 0, not_canceled)) %>%
mutate(canceled = ifelse(is.na(canceled) == TRUE, 0, canceled)) %>%
mutate(prop_canceled = canceled / (not_canceled + canceled)) %>%
mutate(prop_not_canceled = not_canceled / (not_canceled + canceled))

First I select my necessary variables which are; hotel, is_canceled, previous_cancellations. I then group by all of those variables in order to creat a new variable "num_cancel" to count the number of canceled bookings and not canceled bookings for each hotel and for each value of previous cancellations. I then spread by is canceled in order to have a column of the canceled booking values and the not canceled booking values. Then in order to make the table more readable I renamed the is_canceled values. Because the value in spread would return NA instead of 0 if there were no canceled or not canceled bookings for a given previous_cancellation value, I changed these NAs to 0. I then found the proportion of canceled and not canceled bookings.

Below I have graphed the results using geom_point(), geom_smooth(), and facet_wrap() in order to compare the two types of hotels. I graphed both the proportion of canceled bookings and the propotion of bookings not canceled. Even though the graphs are inverses of each other I though it may be useful to see both.

markseg_table <- tidy %>%
select(hotel, is_canceled, market_segment) %>%
group_by(hotel, is_canceled, market_segment) %>%
summarize(num_cancel = n()) %>%
spread(key = is_canceled, value = num_cancel) %>%
mutate(not_canceled = `0`, canceled = `1`) %>%
select(hotel, market_segment, not_canceled, canceled) %>%
mutate(not_canceled = ifelse(is.na(not_canceled) == TRUE, 0, not_canceled)) %>%
mutate(canceled = ifelse(is.na(canceled) == TRUE, 0, canceled)) %>%
mutate(prop_canceled = canceled / (not_canceled + canceled)) %>%
mutate(prop_not_canceled = not_canceled / (not_canceled + canceled)) %>%
print()

Question 4¶

Market segments (the channels in which the hotels get their bookings) play a huge impact in how hotels perform. By advertizing their hotel through the differing market segments, hotels are able to reach different audiences and determing which market segment to adverize the most can help hotels earn more revenue and by extension more profit.

Thus we will explore which Market Segment should hotels spend the most resources on?

One way to decide which market segment to spend more resources on is by determining which market segment brings in the most bookings to the hotels; specifically what proportion of the bookings made to the hotels are done by each market segments.

This is done by first calculating the total number of bookings made by each hotel and market segment. Then, to calculate the percentage of bookings for each market segment of each hotel we use the number of bookings made by each hotel and market segment and divide it by the total number of bookings made by each hotel. We then use ggplot_bar, coord_point(), and facet ggplot in order to visualize the data of booking percentages through a pie chart.

In [117]:
city <- tidy %>% filter(hotel == "City Hotel")
resort <- tidy %>% filter(hotel == "Resort Hotel")

totalBookingCity <- nrow(city)
totalBookingResort <- nrow(resort)

Market <- tidy %>% group_by(hotel, market_segment) %>% summarize(Bookings = n())
Market <- Market %>% mutate(Booking_Percentage = ifelse(hotel == "City Hotel", 100*(Bookings/totalBookingCity), 100*(Bookings/totalBookingResort)))

Looking at the graph we can see that for both hotels, City Hotel and Resort Hotel, the largest percentage of bookings were made through online TA (TA meaning Travel Agency) followed by Offline TA/TO (TO meaning Tour Operator), Groups, Direct, Corportate, etc.

Using this information we can advise both hotels to spend their resources proportionally to the porportion of bookings made by each market segment(ie. spend more resources on Online TA, Offline TA/TO, Groups, than on Direct, Corporate, etc.)

While spending more resources on TA/TO's and letting them advertize on your behalf to consumers can be less work for the hotels, an approach where the hotels spend more resources on market segments that bring in the most bookings may not always be the correct decision.

Hotels should also think about the average money each market segment brings to the hotel per booking and see if they should instead allocate more resources to the market segments that bring in the most money on average per booking.

In order to investigate this, we need to know how much money on average is each market segment bringing into the hotel per booking. First we need to get a subset of the tidied data where we only have the bookings that were not cancelled as these are the bookings that bring in money. From there, we estimate the revenue that the hotels get by multiplying the adr (average daily rate) by the duration of the booking (duration of booking is estimated by adding the number of nights during the week and weekend of the booking). Additionally, in order to determine the correct approach it is necessary to not only look at the revenue brought in by each market segment in general but also look at the trend per year that each market segment brings in.

This is done by first grouping the data by market segment, year, and hotel and then using functions such as spread(), separate(), unite() to create a table that portrays the average revenue brought to each hotel per market segment per year. Then ggplot, geom_line, and facet ggplot are used to visualize this information.

In [118]:
revenueTable <- tidy %>% filter(is_canceled == 0) %>%
mutate(duration = stays_in_weekend_nights + stays_in_week_nights) %>%
mutate(revenue = duration * adr)

table1 <- revenueTable %>% group_by(market_segment, hotel, arrival_date_year) %>% summarize(meanRevenue = mean(revenue, na.rm= TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(meanRevenue))
ggplot(data = table1) + geom_line(mapping = aes(x = arrival_date_year, y = meanRevenue, color = market_segment)) + 
facet_wrap(~hotel)+
ggtitle("Mean Revenue obtained by each Market Segment")+
xlab("Years")+
ylab("Mean Revenue")+
scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2015,2016,2017))

table2 <- table1 %>% spread(key = arrival_date_year, value = meanRevenue, fill =0) %>% group_by(hotel, market_segment)
table2 <- table2 %>% unite(col = "years", "2015":"2017") %>%
spread(key = hotel, value = years) %>%
separate("City Hotel", into = paste0(c("City_2015","City_2016","City_2017")), sep="_", convert=TRUE) %>%
separate("Resort Hotel", into = paste0(c("Resort_2015", "Resort_2016", "Resort_2017")), sep="_", convert=TRUE)
table2 <- table2 %>% mutate( Resort_2015 = ifelse(is.na(Resort_2015), 0,Resort_2015), Resort_2016 = ifelse(is.na(Resort_2016), 0,Resort_2016), Resort_2017 = ifelse(is.na(Resort_2017), 0,Resort_2017))

Based on the table and graph above, we can see that for City Hotel, Online TA's, Offline TA/TO, Direct, Groups have increased the revenue they brought to the hotel over the years while Aviation, Corporate and Complementary have decreased over the years. Looking at Resort Hotel, we can see that all market segments, have decreased and then increased the revenue of the hotel indicating that 2016 must have just been a bad year in general for all market segments to do worse for Resort Hotel.

Additionally we can see that for City Hotel, Online TA and Direct generate on average the most revenue per booking, while for the Resort Hotel we can see that Offline TA/TO, Online TA, Direct generate on average the most revenue per booking.

Thus City Hotel should allocate a large portion of their resources to Online TA, Direct followed by Offline TA/TO, Groups, etc. While Resort Hotel should allocate a large portion of their resources to Offline TA/TO, followed by Direct, Online TA, etc.

However this approach of spending the most resources on the market segments that bring in the most money on average per booking is not the ideal approach either.

Hotels should use an approach that considers the proportion of bookings per market segment as well as the average amount of money brought in by each market segment. Thus using the earlier pie chart and the line graph above we can conclude that City hotel should spend the most resources on Online TA, Direct, Offline TA/TO, etc. as Online TA is both the highest revenue per booking on average and the highest proportion of bookings the hotel gets. Resort hotel should allocate most of their resources towards Offline TA/TO, Online TA, Direct, etc. Additionally Direct market segment has been chosen instead of Groups market segment as even though Groups bring in more bookings, Direct market segment has a significant increase in the average revenue per booking. Additionally using information from the last section we saw that Groups were more likely to cancel their booking rather than Direct market segment.

By allocating more of their resources towards Online TA, Direct, Offline TA/TO, hotels will intern be able to get more bookings towards these market segements and thus earn even more revenue and by extension more profit.

Conclusion¶

We found that peak times for hotel bookings are in the Spring / Summer months, with average lead times and daily rates going up during those times. From the customers perspective, it's important to account for the differences in prices between the two hotels and how they are related to how far in advance the booking is made and the room type. From the hotel's perspective, it would be useful to determine which customers are likely to cancel a booking. Based on our findings generally speaking for both hotels, a higher number of previous cancellations, a larger number time between the booking and the arrival, and booking through the “Groups” market segment were all associated with a higher likelihood of cancelling. Furthermore we also found out that it is in the hotels best interest to spend the majority of their resources on Online TA, Direct, Offline TA/TO market segments as these provide the highest average revenue per booking as well as most bookings per market segment. Hotels and customers can use this information to make decisions to minimize expenses and maximize utility.
